The paper proposes a deep learning framework for multistep traffic forecasting on road networks, which involves modeling spatial and temporal dependencies through graph convolution network and Seq2Seq model, respectively. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Among these, cs.LG and cs.AI are the most likely categories, as the paper focuses on developing a novel deep learning framework for traffic prediction, which is a core topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence. The use of graph convolutional networks and attention mechanisms also suggests a potential relevance to cs.CV and cs.SI, while the application of neural networks in traffic forecasting could also relate to cs.NE.
